review.reviewBody: Overall, I am pleased with this device.  One notable improvement would be to refine the contrast of routes when the screen is set to auto adjust brightness.  Perhaps bold segmented lines would show up better than washed out arrows over a washed out route color?  This issue is unavoidable on sunny days when attempting to prolong battery life.
review.name: Contrast

review.reviewBody: I bought the edge 1040 solar four months ago. It was replacing an edge 1030. So far it’s been problematic. When it works it’s great when it doesn’t it could be quite annoying and time consuming. It does not load my activities to Garmin Connect,or Strava when I finish. Sometimes it takes hours even though it is connected to my phone. It also at times will not sync with my HR monitor or power meter. I’ve tried deleting Garmin Connect and reinstalling it , does not seem to help. I also try removing and then re pairing my sensors. That does not seem to work either. I have also removed and re synced the 1040 with my phone and Garmin connect to no avail. As stated the unit works most of the time but I constantly have issues with it. I’ve tried everything Garmin recommends in regards to these problems to no avail. I must also mention that the  solar charging claims are misleading. The unit will charge very little when in the sun directly. It cannot be charged by the sun. You still need to plug in the unit to charge it. The only solar benefit you get from it is minimal. On a three to four hour ride you might get an extra 30 minutes of battery life. Not what I thought I was buying. However I did get it for way below retail because I bought it after the 1050 was released. That is the only reason I am not returning it. I definitely would not have been happy if I paid full retail. Garmin were a little misleading with their claims.
review.name: Not what I expected

review.reviewBody: I moved from the Garmin 540 to the 1040 Solar. Great choice. The larger screen & solar are wonderful. Never worry about battery life. It is much easier to read while riding with the larger screen and vibrant colors.
review.name: Garmin 1040 Solar

review.reviewBody: I bought the 1040 solar immediately upon release to upgrade from my 1030. If it worked reliably, it would be a marvelous training aid. However, it has been plagued by sensor connectivity issues from the start. Almost without fail, for any ride lasting more than an hour, all of my sensors will drop simultaneously after the one hour mark: heart rate, power, and cadence. When that happens, I have two options. Pull over and stop the ride, Reboot, and start a new ride, or keep writing, where the sensors will eventually return after about an hour of off time. I have created multiple tickets with Garmin tech-support, shared dates Of rides when this happens, offered to send the hardware back to evaluate, questioned whether it could have been a bad batch of circuit boards, and I am always told there is an open ticket for this and to keep up updating my software when it comes out. After a couple of years of software updates, the problem persists, so I am skeptical that it is ever going to get resolved with a software solution. This is a huge issue for analysis of workouts and events. The data are completely missing, and skew the metrics.  I love the idea of this computer, but I have real angst with using it.
review.name: The sensor connection instability is tragic

review.reviewBody: Good upgrade from my 1000 edge. The new features are great and finding them useful.
review.name: Great features

review.reviewBody: The one thing I have always liked about Garmin Edge computers is the availability to have different screens for different bikes. I have five bikes and each one has its own profile. The solar feature definitely extends the battery life. This my favorite Edge computer, more so than the 1050.
review.name: Lots Of Choices

review.reviewBody: I bought a brand new 1040 Solar.  Garmin connect consistently gives me error messages for the most recent ride when trying to sync the Edge unit. I escalated this issue with their support team who literally just dropped responding and has not fixed after having replaced the until once and guaranteed that would resolve it. None of their solutions have worked.
review.name: Bugs in Mac Software

review.reviewBody: I've had my 1040 Solar for over a year now, and it does everything well. Battery life is super (30-40 hours between charges), features a great, syncing with other d vices like radar and heart and power meters is super easy.
review.name: Great gps!

review.reviewBody:
I bought this in September 2024.  Use primarily for road riding.  Have SRAM power/rpm meter and HR monitor running.  3 hr ride lowers battery to low 50%.  Luckily it’s been sunny on every ride I’ve been on.  But this requires me to run screen brightness at full vs auto.  
 Bought while traveling/riding in Italy so not sure who I’ll contact to see if this is a faulty battery? Switched over from polar products and bummed they don’t share data. Especially since I’m still using Polar for other endurance sports and indoor workouts.
review.name: Battery drains quickly

review.reviewBody:
I have had trouble with it and today was a perfect example, it froze up a few minutes into my ride and I wasn’t able to do my scheduled workout,
I don’t seem to gain much time with the solar function. I have ridden in a completely sunny day for over 3 hours here in Florida and only gained a few minutes.
review.name: Disappointed

name: Edge 1040 Solar GPS Bike Computer

review.reviewBody:
Not very happy with my purchase.
Comfortable yes.
Very, very, very slippery. Walked on a wet day in a shopping centre. Nearly killed myself. 
Public toilet the same. Wherever its wet, problems.
Also belief that my feet started sweating in the shoes.
Been told Merrell is the bees knees if it comes to barefoot shoes. Not so sure.
Very comfortable shoes except there is no padding and you will feel every pebbles.
review.name: Barefood feeling

review.reviewBody: Comfortable minimalist shoe, lightweight for summer wear.
review.name: Spacious shoe

review.reviewBody: in starting this review i must say i have the vapor glove 5 and rate that 5star. i give the 6 only 3 stars, perhaps a bit unfairly. it is described as a light trail shoe, and i've been using it on asphalt and concrete...surfaces the vapor glove 5 are perfect for (for minimal runners). this shoe would be xlnt too except for the corrugated sole surface which makes touchdown on harder surfaces than trails, very difficult to get a good feel on. the flatness of the vapor glove 5 sole surface is simply superb for excellent tactile feel when touching down, and thus offers an ability for light impact. the rougher surface of the 6 just messes touchdown up completely, which causes more impact for minimal runners. again, it's partially my fault for not realizing this is described as a light trail shoe, but that description not well stated for the 6, so it is not my fault alone. hopefully this review will alert others running on hard surfaces that this is not the best shoe. thankfully merrell makes the vapor glove 5, which i hope they will be making a long time.
review.name: NOT A BAD SHOE BUT NOT GOOD FOR HARD SURFACES

review.reviewBody: Can't wait to get the other colour to complete my collection.
review.name: Want more

review.reviewBody: Grate minimalist shoe for the price. Is a perfect fit to listed size and a great addition to improving one's health and performance in life.
review.name: Minimalist shoe

review.reviewBody:
I think a little too hard in my opinion. I like that it's a minimalist shoe, but I think just a little bit more protection or cushion underfoot would be helpful. 
If you are looking for a truly light minimal shoe, this is about as light as it gets. Probably about a 5 mm sole
review.name: Nice shoe, but maybe a bit too little protection

review.reviewBody: Good but sole is too thin for me. Makes it uncomfortable on concrete and hard floors. Also I measured my foot according to the chart and the size I got was too small. My mistake I guess. I should have gotten my normal size 13. I’d say these are people who are used to wearing barefoot shoes already. They’re very light. Not water resistant at all with mesh upper. Good for dry weather. But again very thin sole so if you’re not used to it already it may hurt for the first while until your body gets used to it. The merrell Wrapt barefoot shoes are much better for me. They have thicker soles and suede upper which helps keep feet dry
review.name: Good quality but too thin for me.

review.reviewBody: These shoes are very light weight, but that is because the soles are very thin.  This might be good for some people, but I need more arch support for my feet.

review.reviewBody:
So far only about 50 miles over rough terrain but the tires roll well
As per other comments- they deflate faster than many others but that’s the price you pay for supple sidewalls
review.name: Fast rolling supple and light

review.reviewBody: I've got three of these in service (one for a spare wheel) and I've had quite good luck with them. I converted a Specialized Roubaix to a pseudo gravel bike and the 34s were the largest tire I could fit. Yes, they definitely leak through the sidewall, as I've noticed for tubeless tires in general. I found that adding some extra sealant takes care of the leaks quite nicely. I recommend them.
review.name: I like them

review.reviewBody: I do not usually write reviews, but I wanted to warn everyone about these tires. I am sure they are fine if you run tubes, but for tubless tires, they are horrible. The seams will continue to leak and leak and leak. I even had them go flat while riding twice with no punctures (bead gave out). I ended up returning these and getting another brand. WHen I talked to my LBS, they found the same issues and even stopped carrying this tire.
review.name: Worse possible tire

review.reviewBody: Twice now I have replaced my back tire with these -- twice it has busted on a smooth road with only a small slit across the top of the tread. It makes me think there's an issue with the rubber itself. I ALWAYS check my tire pressure before each ride. I never had issues with sealant but after replacing this twice I am moving on to another brand.
review.name: two instances of snakebites on treat

review.reviewBody:
I have no gripes about how the tire goes on the rim or how it rides, pretty respectable in both categories. 

My (BIG) problem was when it came time to remove them. They were so plastered to the rim I couldn't budge them with my hands or even any of my standard bike tools. Mind you, I've been an avid cyclist for decades and have plenty of experience with such things. I had to finally resort to the kind of thing you're NEVER supposed to do -- whip out big boy tools, namely, my largest vice grips to clamp down and leverage the tire off with way more force than my hands ever would have managed. 

WTB -- not cool!
review.name: Ride decent, but a nightmare coming off

review.reviewBody:
Like others have noted these tires leak air bad when setting up. They are also pretty challenging to get on the rim, but not impossible. The snug fit does give me confidence, but I don't look forward to removing them.

Here's the best advice I can offer for getting these to seal up and hold air and tubeless fluid:

DO NOT ADD SEALANT RIGHT AWAY

1. Get the tires on and the belts to seat on your rim. Pump them up to near max inflation and observe. Air will probably leak out of the sidewalls pretty rapidly. You can confirm this with soapy water.

2. Add sealant through your valve stem. 

3. Replace the valve core and add just enough air that the tire isn't flat. DO NOT PUMP IT UP TO FULL. At most go to the bottom of the tire's recommended range; like 20-30psi TOPS. Any more than that and you will leak a lot of sealant through the tires.

4. Slosh the fluid around inside coating both sides of the sidewall and let the wheel sit on its side over a box or a bucket or something to protect your disks/hub/cassette/etc. for like 10-20mins each side.

5. After doing step 4 a couple of times per wheel, add more air and give the wheel an occasional spin on your bike. After a while you should be losing about 10-20psi per hour; which is way better at this point.

6. Pump the tires to max psi and ride the bike about an hour or so.

Your tires should be pretty sealed up at this point.
review.name: They don't hold air well and run small

review.reviewBody: Installed them and saw/heard air bubbles of sealant out of the front and back upper sidewalls!  Waste of money, sealant, and time.
review.name: Just...terrible

review.reviewBody:
It's true, they do run small.

I wanted to love theses tires so bad, but after running 40's which are 35-38s in other manufactures specs I upped the size to 44. I immediately noticed sealant leakage when they were first put on, but I was hopeful. Sadly they flatted, spurting sealant within the first 5 miles of a planned big ride. That was just the back tire, which I ended up swapping. On a ride shortly after the front tire went. I wouldn't  trust these tires if someone paid me to use them. They are easy to put on and would be better ran with tubes than tubeless, Like I say in the title, skip these, they aren't worth the heartache...
review.name: Skip these

review.reviewBody: 700 x 44?s Surprisingly very easy to install, getting air into the tires is a nightmare. Installed on Zipp 303 NSW disc wheels. Front set up took 3 attempts with compressor, minor sealant leaks but sealed after 5 minutes. Tried 8 times on the rear but to no avail, would not inflate at all.  Called it in to ask for a replacement tire. Hoping it?s just a defective batch, will report back when I get the replacement.
review.name: Will not fill air even with compressor

review.reviewBody: I got the 700x40 tanwall tires for mixed surface riding right from my house  (gravel doubletrack, bike paths, roads) and they perform well as an all around tire. Surprisingly grippy climbing on gravel, even out of the saddle if it isn?t too lose and pretty fast on pavement even when running lower pressures. The tan sidewalls are awesome. Pretty easy to set up tubeless with an air compressor. Had one spot on the rear that didn?t want to seal after a few rides, but some extra sealant solved that. Unfortunately they didn?t measure true to size (36mm when first mounted), but have since stretched out to 38.5 (my rims are U28, so that shouldn?t be the issue). Regardless, great tire. If I were doing more gravel and less pavement, I?d go with the 44s if they?ll fit your frame.
review.name: Great mixed surface tire

name: Byway Road TCS Tubeless Tire

review.reviewBody: I bought this after a big boating season.  I had been struggling with a smaller cooler.  The fit and rigging for this is excellent.  Fits perfectly on the NRS frame of my e-142.  protected latches and strap routing are amazing.
review.name: The GOAT boat cooler

review.reviewBody:
Cooler seemed to be nice at least looking at it online……but here are a few nitpicks:

1: you can’t open the cooler when it’s resting on crossbars because there’s no room under the latches to lift the latch. You must either create some spacers to sit under the lip and above the crossbar to give your finder room enough to lift the latch. One could also drill a hole in the base of the rubber latch to use as a pull cord. 

2: Putting anything  ext to the cooler in an adjacent bay will require another crossbar. 

3: the fit and finish of this cooler is terrible. The lid is not aligned with the base creating noticeable misalignments like a middle school schooler the day before braces. The holes for the locks are completely off and require drilling out before a lock will fit. 

4: I purchased the lime green one expecting a white lid as the picture shows, but my lid was also lime green. 

5: there are no cable or cord retainers for the drain plugs. 

6: the plastic surrounding the hinge rod is noticeably reduced as compared to Yeti’s resulting in a ton of flex and play. 

Yes. It stays cold, just like it’s other $500 competitors, but it feels and looks like it should cost half as much.
review.name: Hmmm

review.reviewBody: Very breathable chamois makes for amazing comfort and no swamping on long hot rides. Awesome leg grippers and the secure fit NEVER have me readjusting so I don't have to worry about chaffing or saddle sores. I've never had a bib that fits this good and I look forward to every ride I do in these. Will be getting another pair ASAP so I can have these constantly in rotation over the summer.

review.reviewBody: Just Perfect!!! I used Assos gto was many years, new chamois s11 design is so better for long distance, 700km - 1000km per week

review.itemreviewed: Equipe RS S11 Bib Short - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I just took these out for a ride this morning. It's almost like wearing nothing at all...in the best way. They fit perfectly! The fabric is cut so the compression feels uniform and the seams are minimal. This led to the bibs really fitting like a second skin. The bib straps have the right length and tension to keep chamois and everything else in the perfect spot, and the leg openings only have silicone dots where they need to be to keep them from moving up the thigh. There were no odd feelings of pulling or tugging in any part of the bibs when on the bike, and at the same time there was no bunching or fabric or any wrinkles to speak of. 
The chamois is very breathable and padded enough to keep things comfy. Their construction and the previously mentioned fit work together to keep the placement locked in. Obviously, longer rides will have you reaching for the Mille GTs, but for race conditions these are great.
I have last year's RS bibs and while I liked them, they were not this good. Assos nailed these.
review.name: They feel like they almost disappear.

review.itemreviewed: Equipe RS S11 Bib Short - Men's
review.reviewBody:
My previous Assos bibs were the S9 and I wasn't a huge fan. When I saw these S11's I figured I'd give them another chance. I am SOOOOO glad I did. These bibs are perfect! I got the longer-leg version because I am 6'1" and I like bib shorts that cover more of my skin. The biggest upgrade over the S9 for me is the leg grippers on the back of the raw-cut leg openings. Way more comfy than the legs on the S9! 

The X-frame bib strap keeps the chamois where you want it. And the chamois is super comfy. Has the features we've come to love with the brand. I can't wait for some all-day summer rides in these bib shorts. They are so light and breathable that summer riding should be ultra comfortable. 

Pro tip: Pair these with the new S11 jersey and you will be looking pro!
review.name: Worth it!

name: Equipe RS S11 Bib Short - Men's

review.reviewBody:
This has been a really good piece that I find myself using for multiple sports. Over the Utah winter i used it as a mid-layer under a shell for resort skiing and backcountry skiing when the weather was harsh. Much better than my light down puffy - the synthetic fill a better choice IMO when there is any chance of moisture build-up. Also wore as outer layer (the slick lining make this easy) on the skin track over a softshell before I got warmed up.  The pertex shell worked great against wind and snow flurries, breathes well, and no tree snags so far.  Very packable and *almost* as light as my down puffy, but the shell fabric is more robust. This spring, I have worn it mountain-biking on cold Moab mornings, and on the approach to the crag. I dont think it is all that warm, but has a perfect amount of insulation/weight for any aerobic activities unless you are somewhere super cold. This is exactly what Rab designed it for and I think they nailed it. 
For alpine climbing this summer, not sure, but I think this may be in my pack over more more lightweight down piece, the improved weatherproofness and resistance to moisture simply make it more functional. 
The under-the-helmet hood is simple and functional. One internal pocket is nice for phone. Cuffs are simple but a touch tight to get over gloves, but not a huge deal. 
The black colour also looks quite stylish and I find myself wearing around town a lot. I will likely also use it travelling quite a bit given its styling and packability. 
Fit-wise I am 5'11, 168lbs, slim build and medium is perfect, trim fit.
Nice work Rab!
review.name: Great versatility

review.reviewBody: I am a big fan of RAB and have lots of their kit which I use regularly. However, the Xenair Light Alpine jacket I have just bought has no ability to tighten the cuffs, so the sleeves hang down over the end of my fingers and I cant do anything about it, so the jacket is not wearable ....and I have long arms! This is a major miss from RAB - which is very unlike them.
review.name: Cuffs too loose to be able to wear - as have no adjustment

review.reviewBody: I bought this last week and it was made in Vietnam. The information was printed on the tights, which I think it is better than a physical label. I am 58kg / 161 cm. The tights (size S) are very tight on my legs but there is still much room at the butt, so when I walk I could feel the butt area a little bit strange. Regarding comfort, Abisko Trekking Tights Pro are less comfortable as the Abisko trail tights I own, but warmer. You can literally feel the compression and tightness of Abisko Trekking Tights Pro when you put it on.
review.name: It is a very good one

review.reviewBody:
Without wanting to sound erratic, these are without a doubt the best item of clothing I own. I could rave about them all day to anyone who would listen. 

I have worn mine weekly now for work and day-to-day life for over two years and no issues. The pockets are fantastic, I can fit gloves, phone, keys, etc.  The material is comfortable, light, durable and practical in any weather. I feel confident and happy when I wear them. I am a photographer/videographer for a living and work in a variety of different environments both indoor and out. When not at work I am busy entertaining my child and exploring in the countryside or going to playdates and the tights look good in any situation.
review.name: Best clothing I own

review.reviewBody:
Ich habe die 1. Generation von Abisko geliebt! Sie haben mir viele Jahre gute Dienste geleistet, bis sie nur noch ohne Struktur waren.
Der neue Generation fehlt leider die kleine Innentasche am Bund! Somit werde ich mich nun aus diesem Segment verabschieden, denn ich habe keine Möglichkeit mehr, meinen Autoschlüssel irgendwo unter zu bringen. 
Sehr, sehr schade
review.name: Kleine Tasche am Bund  fehlt

review.reviewBody: I bought these tights in November 2023 and they haven't lasted a year. My first hike, the pocket got snagged by a branch and created a hole. No problem, just a hole in the pocket. Other small snags from tree branches in the legs creating holes. Then going over deadfall, more rips. Can't really repair them out in the backcountry so the holes just grew. After 5 backcountry hiking trips in them they are no longer useable. Disappointed as I thought these would be durable and last much longer.
review.name: Not durable

review.reviewBody: I am disappointed in the performance of this garment for a one day hike on rugged terrain. I hiked the Dix mountain range in NY doing the loop. The pants suffered small holes in the side pockets and the threading on the main seam in the back is shredded and nearly gone. I was really excited to try these out and love the fit and comfort and dexterity I have in them, however the damage done in one day hiking through overgrown trail and sliding down huge rock on a cliff on my butt have made me concerned if they will last another hike before they are unusable. I assume other pants may not have faired as well on similar terrain. Wondering if I got a defective pair since the review on these are great. Would love to hear from the product management team.
review.name: Disappointed in performance

review.reviewBody:
Another reviewer noted this, and I should have listened.  It is pretty rough on the skin, too harsh for me - itchy too.  I also would note that they show every lump and bump, so if you aren't perfectly smooth, be prepared to highlight that. 
Otherwise they seem well constructed and durable.
review.name: Rough Fabric

review.reviewBody:
Everything is perfect except the inner seams around reinforcement areas. I'm nearly getting blisters. Is it supposed to be like that for such an expensive product? 
I kind of forgot this during the hike, but after a day spent in these leggings, I (sadly) know exactly where those seams are. 
Otherwise great features, fantastic fabric, perfect fit, true to size. I am 164, tights could be a few cm shorter. I usually wear M and M was a perfect fit.
review.name: Almost perfect if it wasn't for harsh inner seams

review.reviewBody: My first pair of trekking tights - glad I went for these. I'm Uk16 and 6ft and find the Xl a perfect fit. The seams are very strurdy and the pockets well placed. Hand washed and air dried several times and holding up well. I like the knee and seat reinforcements, but a same coloured option would be good - as per another reviewer.  Warm enough for wild Welsh winters. The fabric dries quickly and is hardwearing with big dogs and scrambling over rocks. The ankle hole seems tight, I'd say these are a "sit down and ease over the heel" legging rather than put on standing up and pull all the way on. A suggestion - Would Fjallraven consider printing the garment information inside the fabric instead of having itchy fabric labels? I have to carefully cut out the labels with a sharp knife, without damaging the seam, which I'm sure will end in disaster one day.
review.name: Hardwearing and warm

review.reviewBody: I was expecting more rugged material, but these leggings are very thin except for the butt and knee patches.  I can picture them easily snagging or ripping on brushy trails.  I do like that they are thin enough that I don't think I will overheat in nice weather however.  They run small!  I recommend ordering a size up.  The butt patch feels weird, like the waist band has fallen down below my rear end, but I will probably get used to the odd feeling after wearing them for a while.  I ordered the green color so that the butt patch isn't so obvious, and I'm glad I did.  It is very noticeable, but I bought these to hike in and not to win a fashion show.  Overall, for the steep price, I was hoping for something a little tougher.
review.name: Not rugged enough

review.reviewBody: I tried these on a couple years ago and was in between sizes and couldn't make them work. I decided to give them another go and I'm SO happy I did! The green color is amazing and they're sooooo helpful on rocky hikes that require scrambling or hikes in the rocky hills of Utah where you have to slide down on your bum. Plus, I don't think there are cooler looking tights out there. The fit is *chefs kiss*. For reference, I'm 5'5 and 175lbs (for once gaining weight turned out to be a positive thing??)
review.name: Love these tights!

review.reviewBody:
My 2-year-old twins instantly slipped out of the shoulder straps!  Tdiv's 2-star review (and others) also says the shoulder straps seem loose and unsafe.

The shoulder straps lack a sternum buckle, standard on every toddler car seat in the world.  I purchased cheap plastic buckles from the largest online retailer.  Now the straps fit safely and the seat is fine.  Thule should warn parents!
review.name: Needs a Sternum Buckle for Safety!

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: Our almost 2 year old can't get enough of riding on the back of our E-Bike! She asks every morning if we'll pick her up from Daycare with the bike. Easy to install and position on the banana seat, easy to strap her in, but very secure so she can't get out of her own straps.

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: Solid child seat. Works great on my Specialized Globe Haul ST. The adjustable choke on the security tether took me a minute to figure out but once I did it allowed me to slide the seat a little further back into the ideal position on the rear rack.
review.name: Bring your youngling on your next ride

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: Overall the child seat is well built.  Very sturdy once secured to the bike.  I would have preferred 2 different positions, like a normal ride and a “sleep” setting for the kid.  The one that tilts was out of stock.  The locking system is a little cheap but overall it does its job.  One thing that really could use an upgrade is the system to tighten the bracket to the bike rack.  When turning the knob to tighten it’s very tough to turn and i consistently have to meep “guiding” it.
review.name: Well built but Could use a little fine tuning

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: So happy we finally found something my son likes to sit in.  We put this on our ebike and he didn't fuss once while in it.
review.name: My Baby loves it!

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: We like everything about this except for two things. It only has one clasp, so the first time I put my baby in I was worried if it failed. Wished there was a second clasp just in case one failed (like a car seat). Second, one of the feet buckles fell off the first week. Love it itherwise.
review.name: Easy to install, fits aventon

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: I swapped from a Topeak child seat to this Thule Yepp Nexxt because it is the only child seat that fits on cargo e-bikes. It’s a nice seat and it connects to the back of the cargo bike very easily. I know that this seat is made from a cushy foam, but it’s not padded enough for my son. He kept having red mark on his back by the end of the rides, so I had to add in some additional foam I found online. I also wish that this seat had a crossbar/handlebar like the Topeak. My son really enjoyed holding onto the padded bar. Overall, it’s a good child seat and if you have a cargo bike, it’s really your only option.
review.name: Good child seat but could be better

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: I bought this seat a few weeks ago and my first rides with three-year-old grandson have been terrific. It feels stable, and is easy to attach.
review.name: Great child carrier

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Nexxt Maxi Rack Mount
review.reviewBody: I have an 11 month old and he fits very nicely and really enjoys the ride. The clips are secure, but easy to release when need be. East to install on bike too!
review.name: Easy to instal and safe and comfy for baby

review.reviewBody: If you have a narrow toe box, these are the shoes for you. They’re a bit heavy but well made, and have a nice stiff and grippy sole. Unfortunately for me, the toe box was wayyyy too narrow and I don’t even have a wide foot. I even sized up a half size and they’re still too narrow. I have the TX4’s as well and that toe box has plenty of room, they’re almost too wide. I’m not sure why la sportiva makes such a huge variation in their shoes.They were so painful I had to take them off in the middle of a long class 5 scramble since the circulation in my toes was completely cut off. I wish they fit as they are much more rugged and durable than the TX4 (the TX4 lace system is extremely delicate and frays/breaks) and I really like the stiff platform. Maybe the next version of the boulder x will have a little more width in the front (hint hint la sportiva). So for now they get three stars for having an unusually narrow toe box that makes them unwearable for me.
review.name: Beware, narrow toe box!

review.reviewBody: I am on my third pair of BoulderXs. I try other approach shoes in between, but keep coming back. They are comfortable right out of the box and are a surprisingly good rock climbing shoe.  They do well in cracks and can edge. When I was in the Bugaboos I actually ended up ditching my mountain boots some days and climbed in the BoulderX instead (they took strap on crampons pretty well!).  I love these shoes, but gotta say...I wish they put more rubber around the toe cap! Over time I wear a hole in the toe on every pair over. Otherwise, it is a super durable shoe!
review.name: Love these shoes

review.reviewBody: These approach shoes are really comfortable and durable. The soles provide the right combination of traction and grip, so they perform great on trail and rock. They are supportive enough for long alpine approaches, while still being lightweight. They are super well constructed and long lasting shoes.
review.name: Review for BOULDER X WOMEN'S

review.reviewBody: Best approach shoe I've ever owned. As a climbing guide, I'm really hard on my shoes. Come winter time, I spend my time traveling and climbing. These shoes come with me everywhere I go. They are comfortable enough for all day wear, super durable and long lasting, incredibly supportive and sturdy, and they perform really well on technical approaches and even easy slab/crack climbs. I'm on my third pair now, and I strongly reccomend these shoes if you are looking for one approach shoe that does it all.
review.name: Review for BOULDER X WOMEN'S

review.reviewBody: After years of trying to find an approach shoe that fits well and performs, I finally found one! This shoe is super supportive on long approaches and durable too. Ive also been amazed at how well they climb! I sized them to fit like a glove with just enough length so my toes are fine on long descents. I feel like theyve molded to my feet perfectly. (I've got narrow feet) I almost always wear them when Im route setting in the gym and am constantly impressed with the moves I can pull off while wearing them. The rubber is super sticky and they edge really well too. Im definitely getting another pair of these soon the treads are almost gone. You can even wear them with gaiters since theres space on the sole for the bottom strap! Love!
review.name: Review for BOULDER X WOMEN'S

name: Boulder X Approach Shoe - Women's

review.reviewBody: No break in needed, soft enough for my tender sensitive feet, easy to slip foot , great lacing system, really fantastic support on worn out ankles (I'm more stable in standing and walking), will have warmth in ankles as well, regular width is not too wide nor narrow, thick gripping soles is a big plus, I feel much less pain in knees and hips with this boot support. Black color is more of rich tone than a washed out look in the photo. Orthotics slides easily in. This is a winner for me. Thinking of buying another as backup incase.
review.name: Perfection for all the life long scars on my feet

review.reviewBody: Seems like a great shoe, although I wouldn't know because they were incredibly narrow.
review.name: Too. Narrow

review.reviewBody: I bought these for my daughter who works at a horse farm. She needed something waterproof, rugged enough to withstand doing barn chores all day, and comfortable enough to not have her feet aching at the end of the day. She loves them! Her feet are so comfortable and dry at the end of the day.
review.name: Great for being on your feet all day doing farm work

review.reviewBody: Though I bought my originally Hokas for hiking and photography, I fell in love with them so. I wore them out Tried a couple of other styles of Hoka them noticed these KAHA 2 GTX were a newer version of my beloved first pair. Love, love these mid-height boots. Lots of ankle support. The super plush is like walking on air I wear them all of the time. The lacing is easier and stays put. I bought the purple. The waterproof material makes them so easy to keep clean and my feet never get wet.
review.name: LOVE these KAHA 2GTX

review.reviewBody: Hiked up and down Kilimanjaro in these boots. I could trust the boots to grip when needed and was very comfortable in them. Would recommend.
review.name: Hiked up and down Kilimanjaro in these boots

review.reviewBody: I haven't actually been on a hike yet, but I have worn these hiking boots to teach in, and they are super comfortable. I have tried so many different brands of hikers, and these are the first ones that I have really liked. My feet did not hurt one bit after teaching all day long. I will buy another pair when I need them.
review.name: Great pair of hiking boots

review.reviewBody: I've tried SO MANY hiking boots. I thought the La Sportiva's I bought would work but when I started hiking more than 3 miles in them, after a long break-in period, my feet hurt. I practically gave up on hiking boots and figured I'd just wear my Hoka light trail running shoes for hikes. But I decided to hike Mount Kilimanjaro next summer and need to have hiking boots for the summit day that can get as cold as -25 Fahrenheit. I hiked 6 miles with 2,100 feet of elevation gain and loss on a tricky trail with roots, rocks, and bouldering in these boots yesterday and my feet were in heaven. These are wearable right out of the box. They're just what I hoped they'd be: like my super cushioned running Hokas but with the stability of a boot. I no longer need to worry about what boot I'll wear and can focus on training. I wear a 7.5 in my Hoka trail running shoes and the 7.5 in these fit just right.
review.name: Finally.

review.reviewBody: No cushion and the rivots for the shoelaces fub on my ankle bone even with thick socks. I'm a long standing fan of Hoka, but that might be a thing of the past :(
review.name: Not What They Used To Be!!!

review.reviewBody: Am impressed with the waterproofing of this boot and I find it perfect for hiking, field work, and zookeeping. Super comfortable and plush.
review.name: Great boot, perfect for hiking and field work

review.reviewBody: Best hiking shoes I've owned! No blisters first wear! Super light weight technical and high performance boot that makes hiking limitless. So impressed with the feel, comfort and enhancement of this boot. Got me up an 8 hour rock climbing trail. The GTX was an absolute life saver and held dryness through mud pools and the vibrim gripped across slippery faces. I hiked 3 weeks in the Andes and regret not having these for that trip. Excited for the expeditions ahead. Hike will be making a comeback for me in my life with these!!
review.name: Hoka nailed hike

review.reviewBody: These shoes work really well for me. I've enjoyed them right out of the box. Definitely my favorite pair of Altras and possibly my favorite running shoe of all time. Previous shoe was latest version of Arahi, these are so much better.
review.name: Excellent Shoes

review.reviewBody: Best shoe in its inventory. I love these shoes. Great stability and cushion, especially in the forefoot, without feeling to soft. These are perfect for me. Hopefully they do not mess with it.
review.name: Great Running Shoe

review.reviewBody: They are very comfortable with good cushion and great support at the same time. Coming from someone who had foot pain from bunions and plantar fasciitis, these are what the doctor ordered.
review.name: I would definitely buy them again!

review.reviewBody: I have several pairs of Altra & I wear the stability versions. The Experience Form is the best Altra I have ever worn. Support is great and it is paired with best cushioning of all stability shoes.
review.name: Best Altra Yet

review.reviewBody: I love the comfort of my Paradaigm 6's and were my favorite until the Experience Forms. I've been walking and running in zero drop shoes for about a year. Due to some low calf tightness/muscle tension from the increased tension of zero drop, I was super excited Altra came out with a dropped shoe. This has allowed me to keep wearing my favorite brand but takes the tension off my calves. I need a stability shoe and the experience form is my new favorite Altra! The foam is responsive and comfortable for everyday wear and running. I love the color ways and the black looks stylish to wear with jeans or shorts.
review.name: Excellent addition to the Altra lineup

review.reviewBody: The Altra Experience Form shoes are my favorite so far. I've previously purchased the Torin 5, Torin 6, and Torin 7. These did not have enough shock absorption for running on concrete/pavement. My average pace has improved 30-40 seconds per mile with no other change than my shoes. Have been plagued by various injuries from other shoes, but feel incredibly strong running in these shoes. Altra should continue to invest more colors into this shoe - more neutrals (E.g., slate blue)
review.name: Favorite running shoe

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] As a long-distance runner (50 plus miles per week), these shoes have held up great. They have the perfect amount of cushion without feeling too heavy. Also as someone who has had plantar fasciitis problems, these shoes have not enhanced that problem. I really have enjoyed running in these shoes and will certainly be ordering another pair.
review.name: Great support and cushion for long-distance running

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This was my first time trying Altra but I was pleasantly surprised how much I like these shoes. I tend to have a wider foot but these shoes fit me perfect. Super comfortable and great for everything from trail hiking to everyday running. I would recommend trying these out!
review.name: First time trying altra

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I tried these out when I went running a few days ago and they were wonderful! Super comfortable and the quality is great. The shoes provide excellent cushion for your foot and fits TTS. I would highly recommend these shoes to anyone in the market for a new pair of running shoes!
review.name: Super Comfortable and Quality is Top Notch

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] If you're a runner, you know shoes can make or break your runs. From the moment I slipped them on, it was evident that these were not your average running shoes. When you run, having supportive shoes is non-negotiable. These shoes do just that and do it extremely well. These shoes are supportive and comfortable, and I feel I can experience a hassle-free, stable, and injury-free run. The roomy toe box gives my toes the freedom to move naturally, and the secure midfoot ensures a snug fit without any discomfort. The rocker shape geometry and the low 4mm drop work seamlessly together to provide a smooth, quick roll through each stride. It kind of propels me forward, unlike what I've experienced before. It's such a cool thing to experience. The foam is lightweight and so soft, it's like running on clouds! I find myself reaching for these shoes every time I head out the door. I absolutely love everything these offer - the comfort, the glide, the softness, the performance, among many other things.
review.name: Like a coach by your side

review.reviewBody:
I love the Sundancer hat but because I wear expensive hearing aids that can’t get wet I ordered this one as well.

I am so disappointed!

The brim is narrower and the cape in the back isn’t as long nor as wide.  If the rain is falling vertically then, maybe, it would be OK.  But if the rain is blowing from in front or the sides e.g. on a windy blustery day, as is often the case, this hat won’t provide the protection I need.
review.name: Not the best hat for rain

review.reviewBody: I work outside at a garden center. This hat keeps me dry and  comfortable on long rainy days.
review.name: Work outside

review.reviewBody: Great hat. I have 4 of them and wear them every time I’m outside.
review.name: Hats

review.reviewBody: Perfect hat for in the hot sun, especially in Texas sun.  My head and face feels protected. Haven't had the opportunity to test with rain ... yet
review.name: Waiting for a storm.

review.reviewBody: Love the style, but the neck strap tightener was prob broken and hard to use.  Not like the ones on my other Sunday Afternoon hats.  Too much of a hassle to return.
review.name: -Neck strap tightener broken/defective

review.reviewBody: I LOVE Sunday Afternoons hats, have several, but this time I am not fond of the hat. The color looks like tan online, but it is more gray than tan. Ok, I am not pleased with the color but can live with it. However the chin strap this time is just a rubbery piece that slides up and down, not the plastic piece pictured that allows one to squeeze it and adjust it up or down. Is it defective or a new less-desirable design? Not sure but it seems prone to wearing out.
review.name: Is gray, not tan. Chin strap not as pictured.

review.reviewBody: I bought this hat almost 10 years ago. It keeps all the rain away, keeps the water off the back of my neck and down into my clothing, the webbing inside keeps it so my head doesn't get sweaty. This is a fantastic hat. My daughter borrowed my hat when she volunteered at a wildlife rescue and without in the pouring rain all the time cleaning the enclosures. I kept the rain out of her eyes and off her back. I can't say enough about this fantastic hat. I'm a woman but find that men's hats usually fit a little better. This hat is quite large though. When I bought it it came in different sizes, I don't see that often now. I wish I had gotten a little bit smaller size even with the adjustment on the back
review.name: My favorite hat

review.reviewBody: Bought this for an Alaskan cruise and it was sunny the entire trip. But worked nicely as sun protection and looked cute in the selfies.
review.name: Pleased with this purchase

review.reviewBody: Wore hat in rain and kept my head dry. Bought it for an upcoming trip to rainy Norway so I can be hands free when taking photos and using hiking poles. Like that the brim and tail are useful for both rain and sun protection.  Like the folding feature (better than my stiff Tilley hat).  Now my husband wants one too.
review.name: Dual-Protection, Well-Designed Hat

review.reviewBody: We wore our new hats at Disneyland during lots and lots of rain, and they kept us dry.
review.name: Hats made a good trip

review.reviewBody: I know I am being a bit hard with the 1 star rating but given the bottle hasn't served the purpose it was bought for and now sits at home, I think the 1 star rating is justified. I'd also like to add that it seems to be a running theme with the 1 stars and I too contribute to it: the bottle I have is literally impossible to unlock when one's running. It requires way too much effort and has even scratched my nails in my attempts to twist it. I ended up just twisting open the cap and drinking directly from the bottle's opening. Obviously, that does away with the convenience of carrying a bottle with a nozzle. Now, I've given up on this one and it lies at home. It is a pity though, I did have high hopes for it and was very happy when I purchased it.

review.reviewBody: The bottles are great. They work great for racing, especially with the locking tops. I'm able to stow these in a belt without worrying about them leaking. However, the last 4 bottles I've purchased have all came with the non locking, traditional cap. Please just sent me what I thought I was buying.

review.reviewBody: Love this bottle and the soft flask is now my new favorite
review.name: Perfect size for anything under 10 miles

review.reviewBody: I purchased the active handheld bottle about a month ago. As an older runner, I find that I need to drink more while I run. Especially with temps above 75. I wanted something light and minimalistic with a volume that would get me through 60 min/6 miles. This bottle does that. I love it. Its comfortable to hold, no sloshing, perfect volume, cleanable.
review.name: Terrific running handheld bottle

review.reviewBody: Light, no taste from container, easy to carry. Packs down well.
review.name: Great bottle

review.reviewBody: I Have used this flask for 3 sessions now and the same exact thing happens every time, the ON/OFF system gets stuck/locked to OFF and I can't turn it, today I had to use a pipe wrench to get it un-stuck again, and I have strong hands/grip/fingers,  This happens why? during runs when I try to open and lock it, it ends up turning/rotating the whole cap of the flask, they I try to tighten it hard to prevent this from happening and the ON/OFF system gets stuck/locked to OFF and I end up having to take off the whole cap for drinking, incredible frustrating system. I might have an item that is faulty from production ? but this system is not easy to use even when it is *working* , when I have sweaty or cold wet hands it is really hard to operate. I have other similar systems from another brand (not mentioned), and it works perfect every time allways no matter the situation.
review.name: Faulty unreliable ON/OFF cap system

review.reviewBody: Very happy with the product. Very easy to set up and provides the workout I need at a reasonable expense. Appears to be very high quality manufacturing and I expect a lengthy service life. I don’t know if the resistance units are rebuildable but then again I’m 67 and I don’t expect I will wear it out.. I would recommend this to anyone looking for a no frills, effective trainer.
review.name: Good Purchase

review.reviewBody: Replaced a mag trainer with the Saris Fluid 2. It's has a smoother feel, better resistance and doesn't require a cable to adjust it. Its very solid.
review.name: Great trainer

review.reviewBody: Went from a Magnetic Wind Trainer to a Fluid Wind Trainer. Was hoping for something quieter than the prior trainer but the sound is basically the same.  Having said that, this fluid trainer gives the best experience that is closest to riding on the road. Saris sent the item quickly and packaged it perfectly.  I would buy this trainer again and would recommend to any bicyclist looking for a good wind trainer that is priced decently for those of us not wanting to spend a lot to use a trainer inside when there is bad weather outside..
review.name: Upgraded

review.reviewBody: Just set up and only used once but pleased with its design.  My only quibble, and it's slight, is that the instructions are printed too small to be readily read and interpreted.  The illustration of the insertion of the L bolt was misleading and it took me a couple of minutes to figure out the correct procedure.  Otherwise, a fine product.
review.name: Sturdily Built

review.reviewBody: I bought the Saris Fluid2 trainer for basic training.  The first one had a severe leak after the first use, and I asked for an exchange.  The second one was leaky, too.  I wonder how Saris conducts QC.  I don't recommend this trainer to anyone given the poor quality.
review.name: Poor quality, leaky trainer

review.reviewBody: I got this as a gift and I enjoyed it for two and a half years of moderate use.  It was a good workout, and while I wouldn't call it quiet - and it got noisier over time - that never really bothered me.  After two and a half years it broke, and I was informed that the warranty covers just two years.  The resistance unit replacement is nearly as expensive as the whole thing, so I'll probably look for something higher quality.
review.name: Ok while it lasted

review.reviewBody: The Fluid2 Trainer was easy to set up and get rolling. The clutch/knob takes the guesswork out of tire-roller contact. The resistance unit is very quiet and smooth, especially when using a properly inflated training tire. Since this is a basic trainer, it is necessary to manually shift gears in accordance with the gradient or speed, which gives a real road feel. I am using GCN training videos which offers a wide selection of programs.
review.name: Cruising Into the Season

review.reviewBody:
I bought the Fluid 2 as my first trainer. Got on sale at Scheels. This thing is awesome. I’ve been training 6 days a week for 45 minutes each ride with my new Trek road bike. Super quiet and smooth.
I bought the trainer tire and a used spare wheel so I don’t have to change tires back and forth.
Absolutely highly recommend it for ease of value, set up and use.
Perfect for the cold Wisconsin winters to keep moving.
review.name: Awesome Trainer

review.reviewBody: Easy to set up.  Stable & sturdy.  Very easy to insert and tighten down.  Highly recommended.
review.name: Great Trainer

review.reviewBody: I was very surprised when I finally opened the box, to learn that assembly is not an ordeal. Actually it went very smoothly and took less than an hour.
review.name: Easy to Assemble

review.reviewBody: I purchased these on a whim and have thrown out my other pants similar to these.  The cut is nice and has a slight taper in the leg giving it a modern look.  The material stretches and I have not noticed any wear after several washes.  I am usually tough on clothing and these show no sign of abuse.  I bought another pair in a different color I liked them so much.
review.name: Great pants

review.reviewBody: Best pants I have ever owned. I had a pair of the regular Ferrosi pants, they were comfortable, but way too wide and baggy for my liking. These ones are a great cut and have an excellent feel to them. Super stretchy, super light, super comfortable. OR, please never change these. I will be buying more and more pairs!
review.name: Comfortable

review.reviewBody: They're a little fragile but they breath well and are cool. The highest praise I can give them is I keep buying them.
review.name: They're Good

review.reviewBody: The transit pants are a step-up in fashion compared to the standard Ferrosi pants. Granted I'm not a fashion master as my wife reminds me but these are versatile enough to wear climbing or to work. They don't have the zipper thigh pocket but as I mentioned this gives them a slightly more formal look and fit. Obviously it goes without saying that they are comfortable, stretchy and lightweight like the entire Ferrosi line. Sometimes the Ferrosi line is known to pill but I haven't noticed any yet after a couple of months wear.
review.name: A nice upgrade.

review.reviewBody: Outstanding pant for work on the mountain or work in the office.
review.name: Sidewalk to summit.

review.reviewBody:
I have the regular Ferrosi pants as well, and I like that the transit has a more casual look. The tapered calves are nice. The logo on mine is up by the hand pocket so it’s less noticeable which I prefer (I notice some of the pictures it is mid-leg, not sure if it’s different years model, but mine is high near the pocket).
I don’t really need a zip pocket on the seat, so I’d rather not have that. But some people may appreciate that feature I guess. I wear these as casual wear, so don’t need a zip seat pocket. I’d rather have a hidden zip pocket near the front hand pocket if anything, rather than a seat zip pocket. But this is a minor detail.
So Ferrosi fabric with a more casual look. I still wouldn’t wear them as office wear, they still look like outdoors pants.
review.name: Comfortable, casual-looking

review.reviewBody: These pants are a perfect fit and feel. They are stretchy and durable.
review.name: Great pants

review.reviewBody: I wear these pants at the office and at home. They are lightweight and comfortable. However, they are certainly not durable. After a few washes they have picks, pulls, and the fabric is pilling at the pockets. I would not recommend. Very disappointed in the durability. Would not recommend.
review.name: NOT DURABLE

review.reviewBody: These pants lived up to my expectations. I was looking for pants that were light, stretchy, and provided sun protection. Check, check, and check. I wore them in 90 degree heat and didn't think once about being too hot. And even though I purchased them for the outdoors, the khakis look good enough to wear to work. I would buy them again.
review.name: As good as advertised

review.reviewBody: So incredibly comfortable and just perfect in every way.
review.name: These are my new favorite pants!

review.reviewBody: This is a very lightweight sweater, I thought it was a bit sturdier  material.  Also, it does run big.  I will wear it as I like it but just not what I thought it was.  The picture makes it look like it is thicker making it form fitting.  It hangs.
review.name: Not what I expected

review.reviewBody:
The jacket is very comfortable, but do wish I purchased my regular size rather than sizing up. 
I've worn it with the thrift base and a down vest in 30-40F weather and was definitely comfortable when the temps were close to 40F. I can see this being a great light jacket for warmer weather and certainly works as a mid-layer for those going indoor/outdoor. It's a bit too lightweight for me, if I'm spending a lot of time outdoors in the cold.
 Looking forward to taking it traveling!

I purchased one of these on a whim and now I have gotten another 2. These have become my favorite added layer on cool spring days and summer mornings/evenings. The jacket is tight fitting, but not restrictive; it's a great mid layer as well. I find it breathable. I typically wear a US size 6 and own size S in this jacket, since I like the tighter fit which I'll usually wear over a fitted base layer. I'd definitely size up with you want to put more layers under it.
review.name: Close fitting and lightweight warmth

review.reviewBody: This jacket is soft, comfortable, and provides good warmth while being small and light. However, I only wear it for belaying, easy climbing, or hanging at camp because it is not breathable enough for hiking or really anything that gets your heart rate up. The lack of pockets is also a downside but does contribute to the lightness.
review.name: Comfortable, warm, but not breathable

review.reviewBody:
I purchased this on a whim, but I have ended up reaching for it again and again. It is surprisingly warm, but breathable. I have used it kayaking and hiking in the early fall, and just this AM I used it for a paddle on a mountain lake with weather in the low 50s. It's my favorite light jacket for slightly chilly AMs. It's fitted, so it's comfortable to wear alone or over a light t-shirt. I typically wear a size 6 and found the small to be perfect. I might recommend sizing up if you want a looser fit, but I find the streamlined fit to be both comfortable and flattering.
Looks like I'll be looking for more of these!
review.name: So Versatile

review.reviewBody:
This is my go to mid-layer! It's super warm but light. I use it as mid-layer for mountaineering, hiking, ice climbing or as a jacket on its own on chilly days while rock climbing.

The quality feels great too!
review.name: Use it all the time

review.reviewBody: I got both the regular Aconcagua jacket and the light version for different weather conditions. I really wanted to love this one more because of the pretty color and style. However, I wish this jacket was just slightly thicker and I find the size runs a bit big.
This jacket is the perfect weight and fit for layering as we move into cooler weather.
I really like this long sleeve. It's great for spring skiing and layering over a tank top. The white colored one gets too dirty too quickly.
review.name: Great Long Sleeve, but White Gets Dirty

review.reviewBody: Excellent light midlayer for high aerobic winter activities. I've worn this on a few ski tours under my softshell with temps below -15C and had excellent moisture management. I found the medium didn't fit quite as snug as I was expecting (I'm 5'9 and quite slim, typically between a med-small in most brands), but with how stretchy the fabric is I find I can get a 200 weight merino baselayer underneath without the uncomfortable compression effect that some layers cause.
review.name: Great breathable midlayer for winter!

Bought this helmet for my 4 y/o son when we got him a new bike. Within a month, he lost lost control going down a slight hill, causing a significant crash. He hit the back of his head on the pavement. The helmet covers the back of the head and protected him from a serious injury. review.reviewBody: bought this for my husband who is using it as a trad harness. He was looking for something comfortable with durable gear loops. Many other harnesses either have gear loops too small or not durable at all (made of cloth), or the harness part is not comfortable and doesn't stay in place.
review.name: bought this for my husband

review.reviewBody: Runs slightly larger than the momentum. I am a L in momentum and this harness is SLIGHTLY too big when all the way tight. Still was extremely comfy with this on all day long in a t-shirt with a double rack. Crushed hanging belays. Larger gear loops. Rubber/plastic webbing(?) for haul loop.
review.name: Hanging belays extremely comfortable.

review.reviewBody: Perfect fit for me!! Ice clippers exactly where i like them… symmetrical when adjusted to my hips! I guess im lucky about it, but it makes it the perfect harness for me!!
review.name: Everything right where it needs to be!

review.reviewBody: What’s not to love. Everything you need and nothing you don’t. A few gear loops, some padding, and all the adjustment ends neatly tuck out of the way. Highly recommend.
review.name: Simplicity at its best.

review.reviewBody: Exactly what you expect from BD. Good price for good gear. I hang in it while cleaning routes and its comfy!
review.name: Bomber

review.reviewBody: Perfect hardness for anything the world can throw at you. Sport, trad, big wall, this harness is going to get worked!
review.name: Ready!

review.reviewBody: I mostly trad climb and multi-pitch so I was looking for a replacement for my Solution Guide since having 5 gear loops is a must for me. This looked like the most comparable BD replacement since the solution guide is no longer made. Looking at the pictures, it seemed like the harness had a full sized 5th gear loop so I pulled the trigger. Immediately out of the box, the 5th gear loop is tiny, like maybe an 1.5 inches, honestly no bigger than just a small haul loop. Initiated a return once I saw this. Again what is shown in the pictures as a full sized 5th gear loop is actually just kind of a tiny pointless thing.
review.name: Pictures don't align with product

review.reviewBody:
Solid in all respects- used for both a sport and a trad 8 pitch. Size up if you are on the high end of the recommended sizing range. My small fits but unfoetunately the left side loops are pretty far around so using the second loop is challenging to use.
I do like the 5th loop at the back for chalk, rescue gear, bail maillon, etc.
Overall: light yet comfortable and versatile. It should be fine to use indoors on the occasion I do!
review.name: Great Harness!

review.reviewBody:
It has been time to replace my previous harness and as I am looking to be climbing outdoors more I went with this one.

So far it has been working well in fit and comfort.
review.name: Replacement Harness

review.reviewBody: Fits very nicely, now all the troubles of switching gear from gym harness are non existent. Nice to have a set up ready to go at a moments notice.
review.name: Outside harness

review.reviewBody: I have eaten a 100 of these over the years. Great tasting, filling meal at the end of the day after hiking and packing.

review.reviewBody:
I like a variety of Mountain House so I buy an assortment. Lasagna with Meat Sauce is a good choice to go along with the other ones I have tried
I like it!
review.name: IT'S GOOD!

review.reviewBody: This is wonderful meal , highly recommend to anyone
review.name: Excellent meal

review.reviewBody: I could live on this stuff it's so tasty. At least one pouch always comes with me on backpacking trips. I've even eaten it for dinner at home when is get the random craving. It reminds me exactly of the Chef Boyardee Lasagna I used to eat as a kid. Of course it didn't taste exactly like "lasagna," but it is really good regardless. The noodles are chunky and the meal satisfying. My only complaint is that a single pouch is really suited for only one person; two people splitting one pouch of this would still be hungry. I'm not a big gal (5'2" and 130 lbs) and I eat one to myself no problem. These are also spendy and I wish they were cheaper for the amount of food you get.
review.name: This lasagna is my absolute favorite MH ever!

review.reviewBody: I'm glad I purchased these because it does taste great and will fill an empty tummy. But I had to adjust amount of water and cook in bag for 5 minutes longer in order to get the meat rehydrated. Will come in handy when needed, but wish they were a little healthier.
review.name: Adjust directions as needed

review.reviewBody: This is one of my husbands favorites go to. He takes this hunting with him and camping. I recommend trying this one if you haven't done so already.
review.name: One of the favs!

review.reviewBody: The Mountain House Lasagna With Meat Sauce is a very well put together recipe full of flavors.  After several meal consumptions, I’ve found it to be a good single serving for me, a 210 lb healthy male, after a full day of open canoe paddling on a wilderness river.  The packaging is very convenient in the closable foil pouch allowing for a self contained bowl thus eliminating any need for carrying extra containers on the trip.  The bag also seals well, keeping the heated water hot and resulting meal hot during the hydration process.  I have found that it is important to allow at least the recommended time for hydration of the meal, and it does not hurt to allow an additional amount of time, perhaps up to 10 minutes longer, to assure complete hydration.  I highly recommend this product for the great taste, the ease of preparation, the ease of transport and the convenience of a self contained and functional pouch from which to consume the product.
review.name: Mountain House Lasagna with Meat Sauce Review

review.name: Boxy torso fit

review.reviewBody: I found these a little long given I needed a XL but the adjustable straps allowed me to find a good fit for downhill skiing and uphill travel. The stretch panels have been great for allowing the space I need to move. I expect they will hold up well over time but will have to go outside and see!
review.name: 5 Stars for fit and durability

review.reviewBody: I bought these bibs under the impression that the material was sturdy, as it is goretex. OR also markets them as "superior lightweight waterproof coverage for those seeking adventure in extreme conditions for resort, side-country, and backcountry skiing and riding" but these bibs do not live up to this marketing statement at all. I've never owned a bib where the material pulled and ripped this easily. I've barely worn them, and the material and the tears make it feel like I've worn them hundreds of times, which is why I'm so disappointed. I've also reached out to warranty, before writing such a review to possibly find a solution and they have not provided with any helpful solutions. These bibs are waaaayyy too expensive and they don't hold up at all. Do not buy these!!
review.name: Don't buy

review.reviewBody: I was so excited to get the bib and matching jacket for this ski season but was disappointed when, after only 3-4 uses (skiing only on resort, mind you), I found a rip on the pocket of the leg. The cuffs are already seeing significant wear and tear, and I worry they will rip soon too. The material seems so flimsy for Gore-tex pro, I'm scared to use these in the backcountry for fear of more rips. FYI I have gotten 3 seasons out of my North Face bib and Acteryx jacket without a single fabric issue like this.
review.name: Ripped after only 3-4 wears

review.reviewBody: Have been looking for a long time for a comfortable, fitted bib and love it so much. Got quite some compliments on it too :).
review.name: Love this Bib!

review.reviewBody: These bibs are fantastic. I had the original version of the hemispheres bib and it held up for several years. I replaced them this year and OR made some fantastic changes! What I love: very sturdy fabric that is waterproof and breathable, shoulder straps have a well-placed buckle that is lightweight and doesn't interfere with pack straps, the fit is great with room for layers and movement, there are great pockets and the top zippered pocket has a little retainer for your keys, designated beacon pocket, reinforced instep, and generously sized leg openings to fit a variety of boots. I can't think of anything that I would change about these bibs! Glad to have them! Thanks for making such a great product, OR!
review.name: Excellent Backcountry Choice

review.reviewBody: (This review was collected as part of a promotion.) I really wanted to love these pants having had them recommended to me. I loved the colour and fabric with the design including the stretchy panels. However, being tall (especially in the body) I found these to be too short for comfortable movement even having sized up.
review.name: great design and materials

review.reviewBody: I am an OR snow athlete ambassador and I helped with the original design of this bib, as well as this new updated version. I had a chance to wear this all of last year as a sample, and now I have the new kit as well. I can honestly say both the hemisphere bib and jacket are my go to backcountry skiing and skiing outfit. Style, function, and fit all in one package. And this truly is a technical piece, made to hold up to the biggest snow storm. The pockets are deliberate and just where you need them. I love the option to have a beacon in the chest pocket or thigh pocket. Also, it's so easy to go pee with the side zip, its half the exposure of some of the other bibs out there! Highly recommend!
review.name: My favorite ski bib
